obj_root_law_sections_1:
  sectionId (38604)
  sectionNo (1)
  orderNo 1
  title `Short title.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_1_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_1_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38604&sectionno=1&orderno=1&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_1_content:
  string
  line `This Act may be called the Indian Contract Act, 1872.`
  line
  line `Extent, Commencement.--It extends to the whole of India ^1[^2***]; and it shall come into force on`
  line `the first day of September, 1872.`
  line
  line `Saving--^3*** Nothing herein contained shall affect the provisions of any Statute, Act or Regulation`
  line `not hereby expressly repealed, nor any usage or custom of trade, nor any incident of any contract, not`
  line `inconsistent with the provisions of this Act.`
obj_root_law_sections_1_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. Subs. by Act 3 of 1951, s. 3 and Sch., for "except Part B States."`
  line
  line `2. The words "except the State of Jammu and Kashmir" omitted by Act 34 of 2019, s. 95 and the Fifth Schedule`
  line `(w.e.f. 31-10- 2019).`
  line
  line `3. The words "The enactments mentioned in the Schedule hereto are repealed to the extent specified in the third column thereof, but" rep. by Act 10 of 1914, s. 3 and Sch. II.`
obj_root_law_sections_2:
  sectionId (38605)
  sectionNo (2)
  orderNo 2
  title Interpretation-clause.
  content obj_root_law_sections_2_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_2_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38605&sectionno=2&orderno=2&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_2_content:
  string
  line `In this Act the following words and expressions are used in the following`
  line `senses, unless a contrary intention appears from the context:—`
  line
  line `(a) When one person signifies to another his willingness to do or to abstain from doing anything,`
  line `with a view to obtaining the assent of that other to such act or abstinence, he is said to make a`
  line proposal;
  line
  line `(b) When the person to whom the proposal is made signifies his assent thereto, the proposal is`
  line `said to be accepted. A proposal, when accepted, becomes a promise;`
  line
  line `(c) The person making the proposal is called the "promisor", and the person accepting the`
  line `proposal is called the "promisee";`
  line
  line `(d) When, at the desire of the promisor, the promisee or any other person has done or abstained`
  line `from doing, or does or abstains from doing, or promises to do or to abstain from doing, something,`
  line `such act or abstinence or promise is called a consideration for the promise;`
  line
  line `(e) Every promise and every set of promises, forming the consideration for each other, is an`
  line agreement;
  line
  line `(f) Promises which form the consideration or part of the consideration for each other are called`
  line `reciprocal promises;`
  line
  line `(g) An agreement not enforceable by law is said to be void;`
  line
  line `(h) An agreement enforceable by law is a contract;`
  line
  line `(i) An agreement which is enforceable by law at the option of one or more of the parties thereto,`
  line `but not at the option of the other or others, is a voidable contract;`
  line
  line `(j) A contract which ceases to be enforceable by law becomes void when it ceases to be`
  line enforceable.
obj_root_law_sections_2_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_3:
  sectionId (38606)
  sectionNo (3)
  orderNo 3
  title `Communication, acceptance and revocation of proposals.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_3_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38606&sectionno=3&orderno=3&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_3_content:
  string
  line `The communication of proposals`
  line `the acceptance of proposals, and the revocation of proposals and acceptances, respectively, are deemed to`
  line `be made by any act or omission of the party proposing, accepting or revoking by which he intends to`
  line `communicate such proposal, acceptance or revocation, or which has the effect of communicating it.`
obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_4:
  sectionId (38607)
  sectionNo (4)
  orderNo 4
  title `Communication when complete.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_4_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38607&sectionno=4&orderno=4&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_4_content:
  string
  line `The communication of a proposal is complete when it comes`
  line `to the knowledge of the person to whom it is made.`
  line
  line `The communication of an acceptance is complete,`
  line
  line `as against the proposer, when it is put in a course of transmission to him, so as to be out of the`
  line `power of the acceptor;`
  line
  line `as against the acceptor, when it comes to the knowledge of the proposer.`
  line
  line `The communication of a revocation is complete,`
  line
  line `as against the person who makes it, when it is put into a course of transmission to the person to`
  line `whom it is made, so as to be out of the power of the person who makes it;`
  line
  line `as against the person to whom it is made, when it comes to his knowledge.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A proposes, by letter, to sell a house to B at a certain price.`
  line
  line `The communication of the proposal is complete when B receives the letter.`
  line
  line `(b) B accepts As proposal by a letter sent by post.`
  line
  line `The communication of the acceptance is complete,`
  line
  line `as against A when the letter is posted;`
  line
  line `as against B, when the letter is received by A.`
  line
  line `(c) A revokes his proposal by telegram.`
  line
  line `The revocation is complete as against A when the telegram is despatched. It is complete as against B when B receives it.`
  line
  line `B revokes his acceptance by telegram. Bs revocation is complete as against B when the telegram is despatched, and as`
  line `against A when it reaches him.`
obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_5:
  sectionId (38608)
  sectionNo (5)
  orderNo 5
  title `Revocation of proposals and acceptances.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_5_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38608&sectionno=5&orderno=5&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_5_content:
  string
  line `A proposal may be revoked at any time before the`
  line `communication of its acceptance is complete as against the proposer, but not afterwards.`
  line
  line `An acceptance may be revoked at any time before the communication of the acceptance is complete`
  line `as against the acceptor, but not afterwards.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A proposes, by a letter sent by post, to sell his house to B.`
  line
  line `B accepts the proposal by a letter sent by post.`
  line
  line `A may revoke his proposal at any time before or at the moment when B posts his letter of acceptance, but not afterwards.`
  line
  line `B may revoke his acceptance at any time before or at the moment when the letter communicating it reaches A, but not`
  line afterwards.
  line
  line `STATE AMENDMENT`
  line
  line `Uttar Pradesh.--`
  line
  line `Amendment of section 5 of Act (9 of 1872).--In section 5 of Indian contract Act, 1872, hereinafter`
  line `in this Chapter referred to as the principal Act, at the end of the first paragraph, the following explanation`
  line `shall inserted, namely:--`
  line
  line `"Explanation--Where an invitation to a proposal contains a condition that any proposal made in`
  line `response to such invitation shall be kept open for a specified time and a proposal is thereupon made`
  line `accepting such condition, such proposal may not be revoked within such time."`
  line
  line `[Vide Uttar Pradesh Act, 57 of 1976, s. 2]`
obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_6:
  sectionId (38609)
  sectionNo (6)
  orderNo 6
  title `Revocation how made.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_6_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38609&sectionno=6&orderno=6&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_6_content:
  string
  line `A proposal is revoked—`
  line
  line `(1) by the communication of notice of revocation by the proposer to the other party;`
  line
  line `(2) by the lapse of the time prescribed in such proposal for its acceptance, or, if no time is so`
  line `prescribed, by the lapse of a reasonable time, without communication of the acceptance;`
  line
  line `(3) by the failure of the acceptor to fulfil a condition precedent to acceptance; or`
  line
  line `(4) by the death or insanity of the proposer, if the fact of his death or insanity comes to the`
  line `knowledge of the acceptor before acceptance.`
obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_7:
  sectionId (38610)
  sectionNo (7)
  orderNo 7
  title `Acceptance must be absolute.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_7_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38610&sectionno=7&orderno=7&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_7_content:
  string
  line `In order to convert a proposal into a promise, the acceptance`
  line must—
  line
  line `(1) be absolute and unqualified;`
  line
  line `(2) be expressed in some usual and reasonable manner, unless the proposal prescribes the manner`
  line `in which it is to be accepted. If the proposal prescribes a manner in which it is to be accepted, and the`
  line `acceptance is not made in such manner, the proposer may, within a reasonable time after the`
  line `acceptance is communicated to him, insist that his proposal shall be accepted in the prescribed`
  line `manner, and not otherwise; but if he fails to do so, he accepts the acceptance.`
obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_8:
  sectionId (38611)
  sectionNo (8)
  orderNo 8
  title `Acceptance by performing conditions, or receiving consideration.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_8_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38611&sectionno=8&orderno=8&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_8_content:
  string
  line `Performance of the`
  line `conditions of a proposal, or the acceptance of any consideration for a reciprocal promise which may be`
  line `offered with a proposal, is an acceptance of the proposal.`
obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_9:
  sectionId (38612)
  sectionNo (9)
  orderNo 9
  title `Promises, express and implied.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_9_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38612&sectionno=9&orderno=9&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_9_content:
  string
  line `In so far as the proposal or acceptance of any promise is made`
  line `in words, the promise is said to be express. In so far as such proposal or acceptance is made otherwise`
  line `than in words, the promise is said to be implied.`
obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_10:
  sectionId (38613)
  sectionNo (10)
  orderNo 10
  title `What agreements are contracts.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_10_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38613&sectionno=10&orderno=10&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_10_content:
  string
  line `All agreements are contracts if they are made by the free`
  line `consent of parties competent to contract, for a lawful consideration and with a lawful object, and are not`
  line `hereby expressly declared to be void.`
  line
  line `Nothing herein contained shall affect any law in force in ^1`
  line `India and not hereby expressly repealed by which any contract is required to be made in writing^2`
  line `or in the presence of witnesses, or any law`
  line `relating to the registration of documents.`
obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. Subs. by Act 3 of 1951, s. 3 and Sch., for "Part A States and Part C States" which had been subs. by the A.O. 1950, for`
  line `the Provinces.`
  line
  line `2. See e.g., s. 25, infra; the Copyright Act, 1957 (14 of 1957), s. 19; the Carriers Act, 1865 (3 of 1865), ss. 6 and 7;`
  line `the Companies Act, 1956 (1 of 1956), ss. 12, 30, 46 and 109.`
obj_root_law_sections_11:
  sectionId (38614)
  sectionNo (11)
  orderNo 11
  title `Who are competent to contract.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_11_content
  footnotes `1. See the Indian Majority Act, 1875 (9 of 1875).`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38614&sectionno=11&orderno=11&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_11_content:
  string
  line `Every person is competent to contract who is of the age of`
  line `majority according to the law to which he is subject^1`
  line `, and who is of sound mind and is not disqualified`
  line `from contracting by any law to which he is subject.`
obj_root_law_sections_12:
  sectionId (38615)
  sectionNo (12)
  orderNo 12
  title `What is a sound mind for the purposes of contracting.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_12_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38615&sectionno=12&orderno=12&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_12_content:
  string
  line `A person is said to be of sound mind`
  line `for the purpose of making a contract, if, at the time when he makes it, he is capable of understanding it`
  line `and of forming a rational judgment as to its effect upon his interests.`
  line
  line `A person who is usually of unsound mind, but occasionally of sound mind, may make a contract`
  line `when he is of sound mind.`
  line
  line `A person who is usually of sound mind, but occasionally of unsound mind, may not make a contract`
  line `when he is of unsound mind.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A patient in a lunatic asylum, who is at intervals of sound mind, may contract during those intervals.`
  line
  line `(b) A sane man, who is delirious from fever or who is so drunk that he cannot understand the terms of a contract, or form a`
  line `rational judgment as to its effect on his interests, cannot contract whilst such delirium or drunkenness lasts.`
obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_13:
  sectionId (38616)
  sectionNo (13)
  orderNo 13
  title `"Consent" defined.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_13_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38616&sectionno=13&orderno=13&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_13_content:
  string
  line `Two or more persons are said to consent when they agree upon the same`
  line `thing in the same sense.`
obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_14:
  sectionId (38617)
  sectionNo (14)
  orderNo 14
  title `"Free consent" defined.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_14_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38617&sectionno=14&orderno=14&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_14_content:
  string
  line `Consent is said to be free when it is not caused by--`
  line
  line `(1) coercion, as defined in section 15, or`
  line
  line `(2) undue influence, as defined in section 16, or`
  line
  line `(3) fraud, as defined in section 17, or`
  line
  line `(4) misrepresentation, as defined in section 18, or`
  line
  line `(5) mistake, subject to the provisions of sections 20, 21 and 22.`
  line
  line `Consent is said to be so caused when it would not have been given but for the existence of such`
  line `coercion, undue influence, fraud, misrepresentation or mistake.`
obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_15:
  sectionId (38618)
  sectionNo (15)
  orderNo 15
  title `"Coercion" defined.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_15_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38618&sectionno=15&orderno=15&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_15_content:
  string
  line `"Coercion" is the committing, or threatening to commit, any act forbidden`
  line `by the Indian Penal Code (45 of 1860) or the unlawful detaining, or threatening to detain, any property, to`
  line `the prejudice of any person whatever, with the intention of causing any person to enter into an agreement.`
  line
  line `Explanation.—It is immaterial whether the Indian Penal Code (45 of 1860) is or is not in force in the`
  line `place where the coercion is employed.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A, on board an English ship on the high seas, causes B to enter into an agreement by an act amounting to criminal`
  line `intimidation under the Indian Penal Code. (45 of 1860).`
  line
  line `A afterwards sues B for breach of contract at Calcutta.`
  line
  line `A has employed coercion, although his act is not an offence by the law of England, and although section 506 of the Indian`
  line `Penal Code (45 of 1860) was not in force at the time when or place where the act was done.`
obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_16:
  sectionId (38619)
  sectionNo (16)
  orderNo 16
  title `"Undue influence" defined.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_16_content
  footnotes `1. Subs. by Act 6 of 1899, s. 2, for the original s. 16.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38619&sectionno=16&orderno=16&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_16_content:
  string
  line `^1[16. Undue influence defined.-- (1) A contract is said to be induced by "undue influence" where`
  line `the relations subsisting between the parties are such that one of the parties is in a position to dominate the`
  line `will of the other and uses that position to obtain an unfair advantage over the other.`
  line
  line `(2) In particular and without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing principle, a person is deemed`
  line `to be in a position to dominate the will of another--`
  line
  line `(a) where he holds a real or apparent authority over the other, or where he stands in a fiduciary`
  line `relation to the other; or`
  line
  line `(b) where he makes a contract with a person whose mental capacity is temporarily or permanently`
  line `affected by reason of age, illness, or mental or bodily distress.`
  line
  line `(3) Where a person who is in a position to dominate the will of another, enters into a contract with`
  line `him, and the transaction appears, on the face of it or on the evidence adduced, to be unconscionable, the`
  line `burden of proving that such contract was not induced by undue influence shall lie upon the person in a`
  line `position to dominate the will of the other.`
  line
  line `Nothing in this sub-section shall affect the provisions of section 111 of the Indian Evidence Act, 1872`
  line `(1 of 1872).`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A having advanced money to his son, B, during his minority, upon Bs coming of age obtains, by misuse of parental`
  line `influence, a bond from B for a greater amount than the sum due in respect of the advance. A employs undue influence.`
  line
  line `(b) A, a man enfeebled by disease or age, is induced, by Bs influence over him as his medical attendant, to agree to pay B`
  line `an unreasonable sum for his professional services, B employs undue influence.`
  line
  line `(c) A, being in debt to B, the money-lender of his village, contracts a fresh loan on terms which appear to be`
  line `unconscionable. It lies on B to prove that the contract was not induced by undue influence.`
  line
  line `(d) A applies to a banker for a loan at a time when there is stringency in the money market. The banker declines to make the`
  line `loan except at an unusually high rate of interest. A accepts the loan on these terms. This is a transaction in the ordinary course of`
  line `business, and the contract is not induced by undue influence.]`
obj_root_law_sections_17:
  sectionId (38620)
  sectionNo (17)
  orderNo 17
  title `"Fraud" defined.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_17_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38620&sectionno=17&orderno=17&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_17_content:
  string
  line `"Fraud" means and includes any of the following acts committed by a party`
  line `to a contract, or with his connivance, or by his agent^1`
  line `, with intent to deceive another party thereto of his`
  line `agent, or to induce him to enter into the contract:—`
  line
  line `(1) the suggestion, as a fact, of that which is not true, by one who does not believe it to be true;`
  line
  line `(2) the active concealment of a fact by one having knowledge or belief of the fact;`
  line
  line `(3) a promise made without any intention of performing it;`
  line
  line `(4) any other act fitted to deceive;`
  line
  line `(5) any such act or omission as the law specially declares to be fraudulent.`
  line
  line `Explanation.—Mere silence as to facts likely to affect the willingness of a person to enter into a`
  line `contract is not fraud, unless the circumstances of the case are such that, regard being had to them, it is the`
  line `duty of the person keeping silence to speak^2`
  line `, or unless his silence is, in itself, equivalent to speech.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A sells, by auction, to B, a horse which A knows to be unsound. A says nothing to B about the horses unsoundness. This`
  line `is not fraud in A.`
  line
  line `(b) B is As daughter and has just come of age. Here, the relation between the parties would make it As duty to tell B if the`
  line `horse is unsound.`
  line
  line `(c) B says to A—"If you do not deny it, I shall assume that the horse is sound." A says nothing. Here, As silence is`
  line `equivalent to speech.`
  line
  line `(d) A and B, being traders, enter upon a contract. A has private information of a change in prices which would affect Bs`
  line `willingness to proceed with the contract. A is not bound to inform B.`
obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. Cf. s. 238, infra.`
  line
  line `2. See s. 143, infra.`
obj_root_law_sections_18:
  sectionId (38621)
  sectionNo (18)
  orderNo 18
  title `"Misrepresentation" defined.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_18_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38621&sectionno=18&orderno=18&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_18_content:
  string
  line `"Misrepresentation" means and includes—`
  line
  line `(1) the positive assertion, in a manner not warranted by the information of the person making it,`
  line `of that which is not true, though he believes it to be true;`
  line
  line `(2) any breach of duty which, without an intent to deceive, gains an advantage to the person`
  line `committing it, or any one claiming under him; by misleading another to his prejudice, or to the`
  line `prejudice of any one claiming under him;`
  line
  line `(3) causing, however innocently, a party to an agreement, to make a mistake as to the substance`
  line `of the thing which is the subject of the agreement.`
obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_19:
  sectionId (38622)
  sectionNo (19)
  orderNo 19
  title `Voidability of agreements without free consent.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_19_content
  footnotes `1. The words "undue influence" rep. by Act 6 of 1899, s. 3.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38622&sectionno=19&orderno=19&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_19_content:
  string
  line `When consent to an agreement is caused by`
  line `coercion, ^1`
  line `*** fraud or misrepresentation, the agreement is a contract voidable at the option of the party`
  line `whose consent was so caused.`
  line
  line `A party to a contract whose consent was caused by fraud or misrepresentation, may, if he thinks fit,`
  line `insist that the contract shall be performed, and that he shall be put in the position in which he would have`
  line `been if the representations made had been true.`
  line
  line `Exception.—If such consent was caused by misrepresentation or by silence, fraudulent within the`
  line `meaning of section 17, the contract, nevertheless, is not voidable, if the party whose consent was so`
  line `caused had the means of discovering the truth with ordinary diligence.`
  line
  line `Explanation.—A fraud or misrepresentation which did not cause the consent to a contract of the party`
  line `on whom such fraud was practised, or to whom such misrepresentation was made, does not render a`
  line `contract voidable.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A, intending to deceive B, falsely represents that five hundred maunds of indigo are made annually at As factory, and`
  line `thereby induces B to buy the factory. The contract is voidable at the option of B.`
  line
  line `(b) A, by a misrepresentation, leads B erroneously to believe that, five hundred maunds of indigo are made annually at As`
  line `factory. B examines the accounts of the factory, which show that only four hundred maunds of indigo have been made. After this`
  line `B buys the factory. The contract is not voidable on account of As misrepresentation.`
  line
  line `(c) A fraudulently informs B that As estate is free from incumbrance. B thereupon buys the estate. The estate is subject to a`
  line `mortgage. B may either avoid the contract, or may insist on its being carried out and the mortgage debt redeemed.`
  line
  line `(d) B, having discovered a vein of ore on the estate of A, adopts means to conceal, and does conceal, the existence of the ore`
  line `from A. Through As ignorance B is enabled to buy the estate at an under-value. The contract is voidable at the option of A.`
  line
  line `(e) A is entitled to succeed to an estate at the death of B, B dies: C, having received intelligence of Bs death, prevents the`
  line `intelligence reaching A, and thus induces A to sell him his interest in the estate. The sale is voidable at the option of A.`
obj_root_law_sections_19_a:
  sectionId (38623)
  sectionNo 19A
  orderNo 20
  title `Power to set aside contract induced by undue influence.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_19_a_content
  footnotes `1. Ins. by Act 6 of 1899, s. 3.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38623&sectionno=19A&orderno=20&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_19_a_content:
  string
  line `^1[19A. Power to set aside contract induced by undue influence.-- When consent to an agreement is`
  line `caused by undue influence, the agreement is a contract voidable at the option of the party whose consent`
  line `was so caused.`
  line
  line `Any such contract may be set aside either absolutely or, if the party who was entitled to avoid it has`
  line `received any benefit thereunder, upon such terms and conditions as to the Court may seem just.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) As son has forged Bs name to a promissory note. B under threat of prosecuting As son, obtains a bond from A for the`
  line `amount of the forged note. If B sues on this bond, the Court may set the bond aside.`
  line
  line `(b) A, a money-lender, advances Rs. 100 to B, an agriculturist, and, by undue influence, induces B to execute a bond for`
  line `Rs. 200 with interest at 6 per cent. per month. The Court may set the bond aside, ordering B to repay the Rs. 100 with such`
  line `interest as may seem just.]`
obj_root_law_sections_20:
  sectionId (38624)
  sectionNo (20)
  orderNo 21
  title `Agreement void where both parties are under mistake as to matter of fact.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_20_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38624&sectionno=20&orderno=21&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_20_content:
  string
  line `Where both the`
  line `parties to an agreement are under a mistake as to a matter of fact essential to the agreement, the agreement`
  line `is void.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--An erroneous opinion as to the value of the thing which forms the subject-matter of`
  line `the agreement, is not to be deemed a mistake as to a matter of fact.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A agrees to sell to B a specific cargo of goods supposed to be on its way from England to Bombay. It turns out that,`
  line `before the day of the bargain, the ship conveying the cargo had been cast away and the goods lost. Neither party was aware of the`
  line `these facts. The agreement is void.`
  line
  line `(b) A agrees to buy from B a certain horse. It turns out that the horse was dead at the time of the bargain, though neither party`
  line `was aware of the fact. The agreement is void.`
  line
  line `(c) A, being entitled to an estate for the life of B, agrees to sell it to C. B was dead at the time of the agreement, but both`
  line `parties were ignorant of the fact. The agreement is void.`
obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_21:
  sectionId (38625)
  sectionNo (21)
  orderNo 22
  title `Effect of mistakes as to law.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_21_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_21_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38625&sectionno=21&orderno=22&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_21_content:
  string
  line `A contract is not voidable because it was caused by a mistake as`
  line `to any law in force in ^1`
  line `India; but a mistake as to a law not in force in ^1`
  line `India has the same effect as a`
  line `mistake of fact.`
  line
  line ^2
  line `* * * * *`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A and B make a contract grounded on the erroneous belief that a particular debt is barred by the Indian Law of Limitation;`
  line `the contract is not voidable.`
  line
  line ^3
  line `* * * * *`
obj_root_law_sections_21_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. The original words "British India" have successively been amended by the A.O. 1948 and the A.O. 1950 to read as above.`
  line
  line `2. Paragraph 2, ins. by the A.O. 1937, and as amended by the A. O. 1948 was Rep. by the A. O. 1950.`
  line
  line `3. The second Illustration to s. 21 rep. by Act 24 of 1917, s. 3 and the Second Schedule.`
obj_root_law_sections_22:
  sectionId (38626)
  sectionNo (22)
  orderNo 23
  title `Contract caused by mistake of one party as to matter of fact.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_22_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_22_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38626&sectionno=22&orderno=23&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_22_content:
  string
  line `A contract is not voidable`
  line `merely because it was caused by one of the parties to it being under a mistake as to a matter of fact.`
obj_root_law_sections_22_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_23:
  sectionId (38627)
  sectionNo (23)
  orderNo 24
  title `What considerations and objects are lawful, and what not.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_23_content
  footnotes `1. See ss. 26, 27, 28 and 30, infra.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38627&sectionno=23&orderno=24&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_23_content:
  string
  line `The consideration or object of an`
  line `agreement is lawful, unless—`
  line
  line `it is forbidden by law^1`
  line `; or`
  line
  line `is of such a nature that, if permitted, it would defeat the provisions of any law; or`
  line
  line `is fraudulent ; or`
  line
  line `involves or implies, injury to the person or property of another; or`
  line
  line `the Court regards it as immoral, or opposed to public policy.`
  line
  line `In each of these cases, the consideration or object of an agreement is said to be unlawful. Every`
  line `agreement of which the object or consideration is unlawful is void.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A agrees to sell his house to B for 10,000 rupees. Here Bs promise to pay the sum of 10,000 rupees is the consideration`
  line `for As promise to sell the house, and As promise to sell the house is the consideration for Bs promise to pay the 10,000 rupees.`
  line `These are lawful considerations.`
  line
  line `(b) A promises to pay B 1,000 rupees at the end of six months, if C, who owes that sum to B, fails to pay it. B promises to`
  line `grant time to C accordingly. Here, the promise of each party is the consideration for the promise of the other party, and they are`
  line `lawful considerations.`
  line
  line `(c) A promises, for a certain sum paid to him by B, to make good to B the value of his ship if it is wrecked on a certain`
  line `voyage. Here, As promise is the consideration for Bs payment and Bs payment is the consideration for As promise, and these`
  line `are lawful considerations.`
  line
  line `(d) A promises to maintain Bs child, and B promises to pay A 1,000 rupees yearly for the purpose. Here, the promise of`
  line `each party is the consideration for the promise of the other party. They are lawful considerations.`
  line
  line `(e) A, B and C enter into an agreement for the division among them of gains acquired or to be acquired, by them by fraud.`
  line `The agreement is void, as its object is unlawful.`
  line
  line `(f) A promises to obtain for B an employment in the public service and B promises to pay 1,000 rupees to A. The agreement`
  line `is void, as the consideration for it is unlawful.`
  line
  line `(g) A, being agent for a landed proprietor, agrees for money, without the knowledge of his principal, to obtain for B a lease`
  line `of land belonging to his principal. The agreement between A and B is void. as it implies a fraud by concealment, by A, on his`
  line principal.
  line
  line `(h) A promises B to drop a prosecution which he has instituted against B for robbery, and B promises to restore the value of`
  line `the things taken. The agreement is void, as its object is unlawful.`
  line
  line `(i) As estate is sold for arrears of revenue under the provisions of an Act of the Legislature, by which the defaulter is`
  line `prohibited from purchasing the estate. B, upon an understanding with A, becomes the purchaser, and agrees to convey the estate`
  line `to A upon receiving from him the price which B has paid. The agreement is void, as it renders the transaction, in effect, a`
  line `purchase by the defaulter, and would so defeat the object of the law.`
  line
  line `(j) A, who is Bs mukhtar, promises to exercise his influence, as such, with B in favour of C, and C promises to pay 1,000`
  line `rupees to A. The agreement is void, because it is immoral.`
  line
  line `(k) A agrees to let her daughter to hire to B for concubinage. The agreement is void, because it is immoral, though the letting`
  line `may not be punishable under the Indian Penal Code (45 of 1860).`
obj_root_law_sections_24:
  sectionId (38628)
  sectionNo (24)
  orderNo 25
  title `Agreement void, if considerations and objects unlawful in part.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_24_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_24_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38628&sectionno=24&orderno=25&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_24_content:
  string
  line `If any part of a single`
  line `consideration for one or more objects, or any one or any part of any one of several considerations for a`
  line `single object, is unlawful, the agreement is void.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A promises to superintend, on behalf of B, a legal manufacture of indigo, and an illegal traffic in other articles. B promises`
  line `to pay to A a salary of 10,000 rupees a year. The agreement is void, the object of As promise, and the consideration for Bs`
  line `promise, being in part unlawful.`
obj_root_law_sections_24_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_25:
  sectionId (42826)
  sectionNo (25)
  orderNo 26
  title `Agreement without consideration, void, unless it is in writing and registered, or is a promise to compensate for something done, or is a promise to pay a debt barred by limitation law.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_25_content
  footnotes `1. Subs. by Act 12 of 1891, s. 2 and the Second Schedule, Pt. I, for "assurances."`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=42826&sectionno=25&orderno=26&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_25_content:
  string
  line An
  line `agreement made without consideration is void, unless`
  line
  line `(1) it is expressed in writing and registered under the law for the time being in force for the`
  line `registration of ^1[documents], and is made on account of natural love and affection between parties`
  line `standing in a near relation to each other ; or unless`
  line
  line `(2) it is a promise to compensate, wholly or in part, a person who has already voluntarily done`
  line `something for the promisor, or something which the promisor was legally compellable to do; or`
  line unless;
  line
  line `(3) it is a promise, made in writing and signed by the person to be charged therewith, or by his`
  line `agent generally or specially authorized in that behalf, to pay wholly or in part a debt of which the`
  line `creditor might have enforced payment but for the law for the limitation of suits.`
  line
  line `In any of these cases, such an agreement is a contract.`
  line
  line `Explanation 1.Nothing in this section shall affect the validity, as between the donor and donee, of`
  line `any gift actually made.`
  line
  line `Explanation 2.An agreement to which the consent of the promisor is freely given is not void`
  line `merely because the consideration is inadequate; but the inadequacy of the consideration may be taken into`
  line `account by the Court in determining the question whether the consent of the promisor was freely given.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A promises, for no consideration, to give to B Rs. 1,000. This is a void agreement.`
  line
  line `(b) A, for natural love and affection, promises to give his son, B, Rs. 1,000. A puts his promise to B into writing and`
  line `registers it. This is a contract.`
  line
  line `(c) A finds Bs purse and gives it to him. B promises to give A Rs. 50. This is a contract.`
  line
  line `(d) A supports Bs infant son. B promises to pay As expenses in so doing. This is a contract.`
  line
  line `(e) A owes B Rs. 1,000, but the debt is barred by the Limitation Act. A signs a written promise to pay B Rs. 500 on account`
  line `of the debt. This is a contract.`
  line
  line `(f) A agrees to sell a horse worth Rs. 1,000 for Rs. 10. As consent to the agreement was freely given. The agreement is a`
  line `contract notwithstanding the inadequacy of the consideration.`
  line
  line `(g) A agrees to sell a horse worth Rs. 1,000 for Rs. 10. A denies that his consent to the agreement was freely given.`
  line
  line `The inadequacy of the consideration is a fact which the Court should take into account in considering whether or not As`
  line `consent was freely given`
obj_root_law_sections_26:
  sectionId (38630)
  sectionNo (26)
  orderNo 27
  title `Agreement in restraint of marriage, void.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_26_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_26_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38630&sectionno=26&orderno=27&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_26_content:
  string
  line `Every agreement in restraint of the marriage of any`
  line `person, other than a minor, is void.`
obj_root_law_sections_26_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_27:
  sectionId (38631)
  sectionNo (27)
  orderNo 28
  title `Agreement in restraint of trade, void.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_27_content
  footnotes `1. Exceptions 2 and 3 rep. by Act 9 of 1932, s. 73 and the Second Schedule.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38631&sectionno=27&orderno=28&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_27_content:
  string
  line `Every agreement by which any one is restrained from`
  line `exercising a lawful profession, trade or business of any kind, is to that extent void.`
  line
  line `Exception 1.Saving of agreement not to carry on business of which good-will is sold.One`
  line `who sells the good-will of a business may agree with the buyer to refrain from carrying on a similar`
  line `business, within specified local limits, so long as the buyer, or any person deriving title to the good-will`
  line `from him, carries on a like business therein, provided that such limits appear to the Court reasonable,`
  line `regard being had to the nature of the business.`
  line
  line ^1
  line `* * * * *.`
obj_root_law_sections_28:
  sectionId (38632)
  sectionNo (28)
  orderNo 29
  title `Agreements in restraint of legal proceeding void.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_28_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_28_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38632&sectionno=28&orderno=29&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_28_content:
  string
  line ^1
  line `Every agreement,—`
  line
  line `(a) by which any party thereto is restricted absolutely from enforcing his rights under or in`
  line `respect of any contract, by the usual legal proceedings in the ordinary tribunals, or which limits the`
  line `time within which he may thus enforce his rights; or`
  line
  line `(b) which extinguishes the rights of any party thereto, or discharges any party thereto, from any`
  line `liability, under or in respect of any contract on the expiry of a specified period so as to restrict any`
  line `party from enforcing his rights,`
  line `is void to the extent.`
  line
  line `Exception 1.—Saving of contract to refer to arbitration dispute that may arise.—This section`
  line `shall not render illegal a contract, by which two or more persons agree that any dispute which may arise`
  line `between them in respect of any subject or class of subjects shall be referred to arbitration, and that only`
  line `the amount awarded in such arbitration shall be recoverable in respect of the dispute so referred.`
  line
  line ^2
  line `* * * * *`
  line
  line `Exception 2.—Saving of contract to refer questions that have already arisen.—Nor shall this`
  line `section render illegal any contract in writing, by which two or more persons agree to refer to arbitration`
  line `any question between them which has already arisen, or affect any provision of any law in force for the`
  line `time being as to references to arbitration^3.`
  line
  line ^4
  line `Exception 3.—Saving of a guarantee agreement of a bank or a financial institution.—This`
  line `section shall not render illegal a contract in writing by which any bank or financial institution stipulate a`
  line `term in a guarantee or any agreement making a provision for guarantee for extinguishment of the rights or`
  line `discharge of any party thereto from any liability under or in respect of such guarantee or agreement on the`
  line `expiry of a specified period which is not less than one year from the date of occurring or non-occurring of`
  line `a specified event for extinguishment or discharge of such party from the said liability.`
  line
  line `Explanation.—(i) In Exception 3, the expression "bank" means—`
  line
  line `(a) a "banking company" as defined in clause (c) of section 5 of the Banking Regulation`
  line `Act, 1949 (10 of 1949);`
  line
  line `(b) "a corresponding new bank" as defined in clause (da) of section 5 of the Banking Regulation`
  line `Act, 1949 (10 of 1949);`
  line
  line `(c) "State Bank of India" constituted under section 3 of the State Bank of India Act, 1955`
  line `(23 of 1955);`
  line
  line `(d) "a subsidiary bank" as defined in clause (k) of section 2 of the State Bank of India (Subsidiary`
  line `Banks) Act, 1959 (38 of 1959);`
  line
  line `(e) "a Regional Rural Bank" established under section 3 of the Regional Rural Banks`
  line `Act, 1976 (21 of 1976);`
  line
  line `(f) "a Co-operative Bank" as defrined in clause (cci) of section 5 of the Banking Regulation`
  line `Act, 1949 (10 of 1949);`
  line
  line `(g) "a multi-State co-operative bank" as defined in clause (cciiia) of section 5 of the Banking`
  line `Regulation Act, 1949 (10 of 1949); and`
  line
  line `(ii) In Exception 3, the expression "a financial institution" means any public financial institution`
  line `within the meaning of section 4A of the Companies Act, 1956 (1 of 1956).`
obj_root_law_sections_28_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. Subs. by Act 1 of 1997, s. 2, for certain words (w.e.f. 8-1-1997).`
  line
  line `2. The second clause of Exception 1 to section 28 rep. by Act 1 of 1877, s. 2 and Sch.`
  line
  line `3. Cf. the Arbitration Act, 1940 (10 of 1940) and the Companies Act, 1956 (1 of 1956), s. 389.`
  line
  line `4. Ins. by Act 4 of 2013, s. 17 and the Sch. (w.e.f. 18-1-2013).`
obj_root_law_sections_29:
  sectionId (38633)
  sectionNo (29)
  orderNo 30
  title `Agreements void for uncertainty.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_29_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_29_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38633&sectionno=29&orderno=30&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_29_content:
  string
  line `Agreements, the meaning of which is not certain, or capable`
  line `of being made certain, are void.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A agrees to sell to B "a hundred tons of oil". There is nothing whatever to show what kind of oil was intended. The`
  line `agreement is void for uncertainty.`
  line
  line `(b) A agrees to sell to B one hundred tons of oil of a specified description, known as an article of commerce. There is no`
  line `uncertainty here to make the agreement void.`
  line
  line `(c) A, who is a dealer in cocoanut-oil only, agrees to sell to B "one hundred tons of oil. The nature of A"s trade affords an`
  line `indication of the meaning of the words, and A has entered into a contract for the sale of one hundred tons of cocoanut-oil.`
  line
  line `(d) A agrees to sell to B "all the grain in my granary at Ramnagar". There is no uncertainty here to make the agreement void.`
  line
  line `(e) A agrees to sell B "one thousand maunds of rice at a price to be fixed by C". As the price is capable of being made`
  line `certain, there is no uncertainty here to make the agreement void.`
  line
  line `(f) A agrees to sell to B "my white horse for rupees five hundred or rupees one thousand". There is nothing to show which of`
  line `the two prices was to be given. The agreement is void.`
obj_root_law_sections_29_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_30:
  sectionId (38634)
  sectionNo (30)
  orderNo 31
  title `Agreements by way of wager, void.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_30_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_30_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38634&sectionno=30&orderno=31&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_30_content:
  string
  line `Agreements by way of wager are void; and no suit shall be`
  line `brought for recovering anything alleged to be won on any wager, or entrusted to any person to abide the`
  line `result of any game or other uncertain event on which any wager is made.`
  line
  line `Exception in favour of certain prizes for horse-racing.—This section shall not be deemed to`
  line `render unlawful a subscription or contribution, or agreement to subscribe or contribute, made or entered`
  line `into for or toward any plate, prize or sum of money, of the value or amount of five hundred rupees or`
  line `upwards, to be awarded to the winner or winners of any horse-race.`
  line
  line `Section 294A of the Indian Penal Code not affected.—Nothing in this section shall be deemed to`
  line `legalize any transaction connected with horse-racing, to which the provisions of section 294A of the`
  line `Indian Penal Code (45 of 1860) apply.`
obj_root_law_sections_30_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_31:
  sectionId (38635)
  sectionNo (31)
  orderNo 32
  title `"Contingent contract" defined.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_31_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_31_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38635&sectionno=31&orderno=32&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_31_content:
  string
  line `A "contingent contract is a contract to do or not to do`
  line `something, if some event, collateral to such contract, does or does not happen.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A contracts to pay B Rs. 10,000 if Bs house is burnt. This is a contingent contract.`
obj_root_law_sections_31_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_32:
  sectionId (38636)
  sectionNo (32)
  orderNo 33
  title `Enforcement of contracts contingent on an event happening.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_32_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_32_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38636&sectionno=32&orderno=33&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_32_content:
  string
  line `Contingent contracts to do or`
  line `not to do anything if an uncertain future event happens cannot be enforced by law unless and until that`
  line `event has happened.`
  line
  line `If the event becomes impossible, such contracts become void.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A makes a contract with B to buy Bs horse if A survives C. This contract cannot be enforced by law unless and until C`
  line `dies in A's lifetime.`
  line
  line `(b) A makes a contract with B to sell a horse to B at a specified price, if C, to whom the horse has been offered, refuses to`
  line `buy him. The contract cannot be enforced by law unless and until C refuses to buy the horse.`
  line
  line `(c) A contracts to pay B a sum of money when B marries C. C dies without being married to B. The contract becomes void.`
obj_root_law_sections_32_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_33:
  sectionId (38637)
  sectionNo (33)
  orderNo 34
  title `Enforcement of contracts contingent on an event not happening.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_33_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_33_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38637&sectionno=33&orderno=34&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_33_content:
  string
  line `Contingent contracts to do`
  line `or not to do anything if an uncertain future event does not happen can be enforced when the happening of`
  line `that event becomes impossible, and not before.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A agrees to pay B a sum of money if a certain ship does not return. The ship is sunk. The contract can be enforced when the`
  line `ship sinks.`
obj_root_law_sections_33_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_34:
  sectionId (42827)
  sectionNo (34)
  orderNo 35
  title `When event on which contract is contingent to be deemed impossible, if it is the future conduct of a living person.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_34_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_34_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=42827&sectionno=34&orderno=35&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_34_content:
  string
  line `If the future event on which a contract is contingent is the way in which a`
  line `person will act at an unspecified time, the event shall be considered to become impossible when such`
  line `person does anything which renders it impossible that he should so act within any definite time, or`
  line `otherwise than under further contingencies.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A agrees to pay B a sum of money if B marries C. C marries D. The marriage of B to C must now be considered impossible,`
  line `although it is possible that D may die and that C may afterwards marry B.`
obj_root_law_sections_34_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_35:
  sectionId (42828)
  sectionNo (35)
  orderNo 36
  title `When contracts become void which are contingent on happening of specified event within fixed time . When contracts may be enforced, which are contingent on specified event not happening within fixed time.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_35_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_35_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=42828&sectionno=35&orderno=36&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_35_content:
  string
  line `Contingent contracts to do or not to do anything if a specified uncertain event happens`
  line `within a fixed time become void if, at the expiration of the time fixed, such event has not happened, or if,`
  line `before the time fixed, such event becomes impossible.`
  line
  line `When contracts may be enforced, which are contingent on specified event not happening within`
  line `fixed time.—Contingent contracts to do or not to do anything, if a specified uncertain event does not`
  line `happen within a fixed time may be enforced by law when the time fixed has expired and such event has`
  line `not happened or, before the time fixed has expired, if it becomes certain that such event will not happen.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A promises to pay B a sum of money if a certain ship returns within a year. The contract may be enforced if the ship`
  line `returns within the year, and becomes void if the ship is burnt within the year.`
  line
  line `(b) A promises to pay B a sum of money if a certain ship does not return within a year. The contract may be enforced if the`
  line `ship does not return within the year, or is burnt within the year.`
obj_root_law_sections_35_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_36:
  sectionId (38640)
  sectionNo (36)
  orderNo 37
  title `Agreement contingent on impossible events void.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_36_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_36_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38640&sectionno=36&orderno=37&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_36_content:
  string
  line `Contingent agreements to do or not to do`
  line `anything, if an impossible event happens, are void, whether the impossibility of the event is known or not`
  line `to the parties to the agreement at the time when it is made.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A agrees to pay B 1,000 rupees if two straight lines should enclose a space. The agreement is void.`
  line
  line `(b) A agrees to pay B 1,000 rupees if B will marry A's daughter C. C was dead at the time of the agreement. The agreement`
  line `is void.`
obj_root_law_sections_36_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_37:
  sectionId (38641)
  sectionNo (37)
  orderNo 38
  title `Obligation of parties to contracts.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_37_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_37_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38641&sectionno=37&orderno=38&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_37_content:
  string
  line `The parties to a contract must either perform, or offer to`
  line `perform, their respective promises, unless such performance is dispensed with or excused under the`
  line `provisions of this Act, or of any other law.`
  line
  line `Promises bind the representatives of the promisors in case of the death of such promisors before`
  line `performance, unless a contrary intention appears from the contract.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A promises to deliver goods to B on a certain day on payment of Rs. 1,000. A dies before that day. A's representatives`
  line `are bound to deliver the goods to B, and B is bound to pay the Rs. 1,000 to A's representatives.`
  line
  line `(b) A promises to paint a picture for B by a certain day, at a certain price. A dies before the day. The contract cannot be`
  line `enforced either by A's representatives or by B.`
obj_root_law_sections_37_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_38:
  sectionId (38642)
  sectionNo (38)
  orderNo 39
  title `Effect of refusal to accept offer of performance.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_38_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_38_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38642&sectionno=38&orderno=39&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_38_content:
  string
  line `Where a promisor has made an offer of`
  line `performance to the promisee, and the offer has not been accepted, the promisor is not responsible for`
  line `non-performance, nor does he thereby lose his rights under the contract.`
  line
  line `Every such offer must fulfil the following conditions:—`
  line
  line `(1) it must be unconditional;`
  line
  line `(2) it must be made at a proper time and place, and under such circumstances that the person to`
  line `whom it is made may have a reasonable opportunity of ascertaining that the person by whom it is made is`
  line `able and willing there and then to do the whole of what he is bound by his promise to do;`
  line
  line `(3) if the offer is an offer to deliver anything to the promisee, the promisee must have a`
  line `reasonable opportunity of seeing that the thing offered is the thing which the promisor is bound by his`
  line `promise to deliver.`
  line
  line `An offer to one of several joint promisees has the same legal consequences as an offer to all of them.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A contracts to deliver to B at his warehouse, on the 1st March, 1873, 100 bales of cotton of a particular quality. In order to`
  line `make an offer of a performance with the effect stated in this section, A must bring the cotton to B's warehouse, on the appointed`
  line `day, under such circumstances that B may have a reasonable opportunity of satisfying himself that the thing offered is cotton of`
  line `the quality contracted for, and that there are 100 bales.`
obj_root_law_sections_38_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_39:
  sectionId (38643)
  sectionNo (39)
  orderNo 40
  title `Effect of refusal of party to perform promise wholly.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_39_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_39_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38643&sectionno=39&orderno=40&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_39_content:
  string
  line `When a party to a contract has refused`
  line `to perform, or disabled himself from performing, his promise in its entirety, the promisee may put an end`
  line `to the contract, unless he has signified, by words or conduct, his acquiescence in its continuance.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A, a singer, enters into a contract with B, the manager of a theatre, to sing at his theatre two nights in every week during`
  line `the next two months, and B engages to pay her 100 rupees for each night's performance. On the sixth night A wilfully absents`
  line `herself from the theatre. B is at liberty to put an end to the contract.`
  line
  line `(b) A, a singer, enters into a contract with B, the manager of a theatre, to sing at his theatre two night' in every week during`
  line `the next two months, and B engages to pay her at the rate of 100 rupees for each night. On the sixth night, A wilfully absents`
  line `herself. With the assent of B, A sings on the seventh night. B has signified his acquiescence in the continuance of the contract,`
  line `and cannot now put an end to it, but is entitled to compensation for the damage sustained by him through A's failure to sing on`
  line `the sixth night.`
obj_root_law_sections_39_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_40:
  sectionId (38644)
  sectionNo (40)
  orderNo 41
  title `Person by whom promise is to be performed.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_40_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_40_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38644&sectionno=40&orderno=41&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_40_content:
  string
  line `If it appears from the nature of the case that it`
  line `was the intention of the parties to any contract that any promise contained in it should be performed by`
  line `the promisor himself, such promise must be performed by the promisor. In other cases, the promisor or`
  line `his representatives may employ a competent person to perform it.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A promises to pay B a sum of money. A may perform this promise, either by personally paying the money to B or by`
  line `causing it to be paid to B by another ; and, if A dies before the time appointed for payment, his representatives must perform the`
  line `promise, or employ some proper person to do so.`
  line
  line `(b) A promises to paint a picture for B. A must perform this promise personally.`
obj_root_law_sections_40_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_41:
  sectionId (38645)
  sectionNo (41)
  orderNo 42
  title `Effect of accepting performance from third person.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_41_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_41_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38645&sectionno=41&orderno=42&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_41_content:
  string
  line `When a promisee accepts performance`
  line `of the promise from a third person, he cannot afterwards enforce it against the promisor.`
obj_root_law_sections_41_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_42:
  sectionId (38646)
  sectionNo (42)
  orderNo 43
  title `Devolution of joint liabilities.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_42_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_42_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38646&sectionno=42&orderno=43&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_42_content:
  string
  line `When two or more persons have made a joint promise, then,`
  line `unless a contrary intention appears by the contract, all such persons, during their joint lives, and, after the`
  line `death of any of them, his representative jointly with the survivor or survivors, and, after the death of the`
  line `last survivor, the representatives of all jointly, must fulfil the promise.`
obj_root_law_sections_42_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_43:
  sectionId (38647)
  sectionNo (43)
  orderNo 44
  title `Any one of joint promisors may be compelled to perform.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_43_content
  footnotes `1. Subs. by Act 12 of 1891, s. 2 and the Second Schedule, Pt. I, for "one".`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38647&sectionno=43&orderno=44&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_43_content:
  string
  line `When two or more persons make`
  line `a joint promise, the promisee may, in the absence of express agreement to the contrary, compel any ^1`
  line [one
  line `or more] of such joint promisors to perform the whole of the promise.`
  line
  line `Each promisor may compel contribution.Each of two or more joint promisors may compel every`
  line `other joint promisor to contribute equally with himself to the performance of the promise, unless a`
  line `contrary intention appears from the contract.`
  line
  line `Sharing of loss by default in contribution.If any one of two or more joint promisors makes`
  line `default in such contribution, the remaining joint promisors must bear the loss arising from such default in`
  line `equal shares.`
  line
  line `Explanation.Nothing in this section shall prevent a surety from recovering from his principal,`
  line `payments made by the surety on behalf of the principal, or entitle the principal to recover anything from`
  line `the surety on account of payments made by the principal.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A, B and C jointly promise to pay D 3,000 rupees. D may compel either A or B or C to pay him 3,000 rupees.`
  line
  line `(b) A, B and C jointly promise to pay D the sum of 3,000 rupees. C is compelled to pay the whole. A is insolvent, but his`
  line `assets are sufficient to pay one-half of his debts. C is entitled to receive 500 rupees from A's estate, and 1,250 rupees from B.`
  line
  line `(c) A, B and C are under a joint promise to pay D 3,000 rupees. C is unable to pay anything, and A is compelled to pay the`
  line `whole. A is entitled to receive 1,500 rupees from B.`
  line
  line `(d) A, B and C are under a joint promise to pay D 3,000 rupees, A and B being only sureties for C. C fails to pay. A and B`
  line `are compelled to pay the whole sum. They are entitled to recover it from C.`
obj_root_law_sections_44:
  sectionId (38648)
  sectionNo (44)
  orderNo 45
  title `Effect of release of one joint promisor.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_44_content
  footnotes `1. See s. 138, infra.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38648&sectionno=44&orderno=45&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_44_content:
  string
  line `Where two or more persons have made a joint`
  line `promise, a release of one of such joint promisors by the promisee does not discharge the other joint`
  line `promisor or joint promisors neither does it free the joint promisors so released from responsibility to the`
  line `other joint promisor or joint promisors.^1`
obj_root_law_sections_45:
  sectionId (38649)
  sectionNo (45)
  orderNo 46
  title `Devolution of joint rights.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_45_content
  footnotes `1. For an exception to s. 45 in case of Government securities, see the Public Debt Act, 1944 (18 of 1944). s. 8.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38649&sectionno=45&orderno=46&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_45_content:
  string
  line `When a person has made a promise to two or more persons jointly,`
  line `then, unless a contrary intention appears from the contract, the right to claim performance rests, as`
  line `between him and them, with them during their joint lives, and, after the death of any of them, with the`
  line `representative of such deceased person jointly with the survivor or survivors, and, after the death of the`
  line `last survivor, with the representatives of all jointly.^1`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A, in consideration of 5,000 rupees, lent to him by B and C, promises B and C jointly to repay them that sum with interest`
  line `on a day specified. B dies. The right to claim performance rests with B's representative jointly with C during C's life, and after`
  line `the death of C with the representatives of B and C jointly.`
obj_root_law_sections_46:
  sectionId (38650)
  sectionNo (46)
  orderNo 47
  title `Time for performance of promise, when no application is to be made and no time is specified.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_46_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_46_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38650&sectionno=46&orderno=47&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_46_content:
  string
  line `Where, by the contract, a promisor is to perform his promise without application by the`
  line `promisee, and no time for performance is specified, the engagement must be performed within a`
  line `reasonable time.`
  line
  line `Explanation.—The question "what is a reasonable time" is, in each particular case, a question of fact.`
obj_root_law_sections_46_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_47:
  sectionId (42829)
  sectionNo (47)
  orderNo 48
  title `Time and place for performance of promise`
  content obj_root_law_sections_47_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_47_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=42829&sectionno=47&orderno=48&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_47_content:
  string
  line `When a promise is to be performed on a certain day, and the promisor has undertaken to perform`
  line `it without application by the promisee, the promisor may perform it at any time during the usual hours of`
  line `business on such day and at the place at which the promise ought to be performed.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A promises to deliver goods at B's warehouse on the first January. On that day A brings the goods to B's warehouse, but`
  line `after the usual hour for closing it, and they are not received. A has not performed his promise.`
obj_root_law_sections_47_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_48:
  sectionId (38652)
  sectionNo (48)
  orderNo 49
  title `Application for performance on certain day to be at proper time and place.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_48_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_48_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38652&sectionno=48&orderno=49&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_48_content:
  string
  line `When a`
  line `promise is to be performed on a certain day, and the promisor has not undertaken to perform it without`
  line `application by the promisee, it is the duty of the, promisee to apply for performance at a proper place and`
  line `within the usual hours of business.`
  line
  line `Explanation.—The question "what is a proper time and place" is, in each particular case, a question`
  line `of fact.`
obj_root_law_sections_48_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_49:
  sectionId (42831)
  sectionNo (49)
  orderNo 50
  title `Place for performance of promise, where no application to be made and no place fixed for performance.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_49_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_49_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=42831&sectionno=49&orderno=50&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_49_content:
  string
  line `When a promise is to be performed without application by the promisee, and no place is`
  line `fixed for the performance of it, it is the duty of the promisor to apply to the promisee to appoint a`
  line `reasonable place for the performance of the promise, and to perform it at such place.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A undertakes to deliver a thousand maunds of jute to B on a fixed day. A must apply to B to appoint a reasonable place for`
  line `the purpose of receiving it, and must deliver it to him at such place.`
obj_root_law_sections_49_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_50:
  sectionId (38654)
  sectionNo (50)
  orderNo 51
  title `Performance in manner or at time prescribed or sanctioned by promise.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_50_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_50_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38654&sectionno=50&orderno=51&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_50_content:
  string
  line `The performance`
  line `of any promise may be made in any manner, or at any time which the promisee prescribes or sanctions.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) B owes A 2,000 rupees. A desires B to pay the amount to A's account with C, a banker. B, who also banks with C,`
  line `orders the amount to be transferred from his account to A's credit, and this is done by C. Afterwards, and before A knows of the`
  line `transfer, C fails. There has been a good payment by B.`
  line
  line `(b) A and B are mutually indebted. A and B settle an account by setting off one item against another, and B pays A the`
  line `balance found to be due from him upon such settlement. This amounts to a payment by A and B, respectively, of the sums which`
  line `they owed to each other.`
  line
  line `(c) A owes B 2,000 rupees. B accepts some of A's goods in reduction of the debt. The delivery of goods operates as a part`
  line payment.
  line
  line `(d) A desires B, who owes him Rs. 100, to send him a note for Rs. 100 by post. The debt is discharged as soon as B puts into`
  line `the post a letter containing the note duly addressed to A.`
obj_root_law_sections_50_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_51:
  sectionId (38655)
  sectionNo (51)
  orderNo 52
  title `Promisor not bound to perform, unless reciprocal promisee ready and willing to perform.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_51_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_51_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38655&sectionno=51&orderno=52&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_51_content:
  string
  line `When a contract consists of reciprocal promises to be simultaneously performed, no promisor`
  line `need perform his promise unless the promisee is ready and willing to perform his reciprocal promise.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A and B contract that A shall deliver goods to B to be paid for by B on delivery.`
  line
  line `A need not deliver the goods, unless B is ready and willing to pay for the goods on delivery.`
  line
  line `B need not pay for the goods, unless A is ready and willing to deliver them on payment.`
  line
  line `(b) A and B contract that A shall deliver goods to B at a price to be paid by instalments, the first instalment to be paid on`
  line delivery.
  line
  line `A need not deliver, unless B is ready and willing to pay the first instalment on delivery.`
  line
  line `B need not pay the first instalment, unless A is ready and willing to deliver the goods on payment of the first instalment.`
obj_root_law_sections_51_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_52:
  sectionId (38656)
  sectionNo (52)
  orderNo 53
  title `Order of performance of reciprocal promises.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_52_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_52_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38656&sectionno=52&orderno=53&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_52_content:
  string
  line `Where the order in which reciprocal promises`
  line `are to be performed is expressly fixed by the contract, they shall be performed in that order; and where the`
  line `order is not expressly fixed by the contract, they shall be performed in that order which the nature of the`
  line `transaction requires.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A and B contract that A shall build a house for B at a fixed price. As promise to build the house must be performed`
  line `before B's promise to pay for it.`
  line
  line `(b) A and B contract that A shall make over his stock-in-trade to B at a fixed price, and B promises to give security for the`
  line `payment of the money. A's promise need not be performed until the security is given, for the nature of the transaction requires`
  line `that A should have security before he delivers up his stock.`
obj_root_law_sections_52_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_53:
  sectionId (38657)
  sectionNo (53)
  orderNo 54
  title `Liability of party preventing event on which the contract is to take effect.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_53_content
  footnotes `1. See s. 73, infra.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38657&sectionno=53&orderno=54&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_53_content:
  string
  line `When a contract`
  line `contains reciprocal promises, and one party to the contract prevents the other from performing his`
  line `promise, the contract becomes voidable at the option of the party so prevented; and he is entitled to`
  line `compensation ^`
  line `from the other party for any loss which he may sustain in consequence of the nonperformance of the contract.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A and B contract that B shall execute certain work for A for a thousand rupees. B is ready and willing to execute the work`
  line `accordingly, but A prevents him from doing so. The contract is voidable at the option of B; and, if he elects to rescind it, he is`
  line `entitled to recover from A compensation for any loss which he has incurred by its non-performance.`
obj_root_law_sections_54:
  sectionId (42830)
  sectionNo (54)
  orderNo 55
  title `Effect of default as to that promise which should be first performed, in contract consisting of reciprocal promises.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_54_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_54_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=42830&sectionno=54&orderno=55&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_54_content:
  string
  line `When a contract consists of reciprocal promises, such that one of them cannot`
  line `be performed, or that its performance cannot be claimed till the other has been performed, and the`
  line `promisor of the promise last mentioned fails to perform it, such promisor cannot claim the performance of`
  line `the reciprocal promise, and must make compensation to the other party to the contract for any loss which`
  line `such other party may sustain by the non-performance of the contract.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A hires B's ship to take in and convey, from Calcutta to the Mauritius, a cargo to be provided by A, B receiving a certain`
  line `freight for its conveyance. A does not provide any cargo for the ship. A cannot claim the performance of B's promise, and must`
  line `make compensation to B for the loss which B sustains by the non-performance of the contract.`
  line
  line `(b) A contracts with B to execute certain builder's work for a fixed price, B supplying the scaffolding and timber necessary`
  line `for the work. B refuses to furnish any scaffolding or timber, and the work cannot be executed. A need not execute the work, and`
  line `B is bound to make compensation to A for any loss caused to him by the non-performance of the contract.`
  line
  line `(c) A contracts with B to deliver to him, at a specified price, certain merchandise on board a ship which cannot arrive for a`
  line `month, and B engages to pay for the merchandise within a week from the date of the contract. B does not pay within the week.`
  line `A's promise to deliver need not be performed, and B must make compensation.`
  line
  line `(d) A promises B to sell him one hundred bales of merchandise, to be delivered next day, and B promises A to pay for them`
  line `within a month. A does not deliver according to his promise. B's promise to pay need not be performed, and A must make`
  line compensation.
obj_root_law_sections_54_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_55:
  sectionId (38659)
  sectionNo (55)
  orderNo 56
  title `Effect of failure to perform at fixed time, in contract in which time is essential.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_55_content
  footnotes `1. C.f. ss. 62 and 63, infra.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38659&sectionno=55&orderno=56&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_55_content:
  string
  line `When a`
  line `party to a contract promises to do a certain thing at or before a specified time, or certain things at or`
  line `before specified times, and fails to do any such thing at or before the specified time, the contract, or so`
  line `much of it as has not been performed, becomes voidable at the option of the promisee, if the intention of`
  line `the parties was that time should be of the essence of the contract.`
  line
  line `Effect of such failure when time is not essential.--If it was not the intention of the parties that time`
  line `should be of the essence of the contract, the contract does not become voidable by the failure to do such`
  line `thing at or before the specified time; but the promisee is entitled to compensation from the promisor for`
  line `any loss occasioned to him by such failure.`
  line
  line `Effect of acceptance of performance at time other than that agreed upon.--If, in case of a`
  line `contract voidable on account of the promisor's failure to perform his promise at the time agreed, the`
  line `promisee accepts performance of such promise at any time other than that agreed, the promisee cannot`
  line `claim compensation for any loss occasioned by the non-performance of the promise at the time agreed,`
  line `unless, at the time of such acceptance, he gives notice to the promisor of his intention to do so.^1`
  line
  line `STATE AMENDMENT`
  line
  line `Uttar Pradesh.--`
  line
  line `Amendment of section 55.--In section 55 of the Principal Act, in the third paragraph, for the words`
  line `"unless at the time of such acceptance he gives notice to the promiser of his intention to do so", the words`
  line `"where at the time of such acceptance he has waived his right to do so" shall be substituted."`
  line
  line `[Vide Uttar Pradesh 57 of 1976, s. 26]`
obj_root_law_sections_56:
  sectionId (38660)
  sectionNo (56)
  orderNo 57
  title `Agreement to do impossible act.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_56_content
  footnotes `1. See s. 65, infra.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38660&sectionno=56&orderno=57&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_56_content:
  string
  line `An agreement to do an act impossible in itself is void.`
  line
  line `Contract to do an act afterwards becoming impossible or unlawful.—A contract to do an act`
  line `which, after the contract is made, becomes impossible, or, by reason of some event which the promisor`
  line `could not prevent, unlawful, becomes void when the act becomes impossible or unlawful.^1`
  line
  line `Compensation for loss through non-performance of act known to be impossible or unlawful.—Where one person has promised to do something which he knew, or, with reasonable diligence, might`
  line `have known, and which the promisee did not know, to be impossible or unlawful, such promisor must`
  line `make compensation to such promisee for any loss which such promisee sustains through the nonperformance of the promise.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A agrees with B to discover treasure by magic. The agreement is void:`
  line
  line `(b) A and B contract to marry each other. Before the time fixed for the marriage,. A goes mad. The contract becomes void.`
  line
  line `(c) A contracts to marry B, being already married to C, and being forbidden by the law to which he is subject to practise`
  line `polygamy, A must make compensation to B for the loss caused to her by the non-performance of his promise.`
  line
  line `(d) A contracts to take in cargo for B at a foreign port. A's Government afterwards declares war against the country in which`
  line `the port is situated. The contract becomes void when war is declared.`
  line
  line `(e) A contracts to act at a theatre for six months in consideration of a sum paid in advance by B. On several occasions A is`
  line `too ill to act. The contract to act on those occasions becomes void.`
obj_root_law_sections_57:
  sectionId (38661)
  sectionNo (57)
  orderNo 58
  title `Reciprocal promise to do things legal, and also other things illegal.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_57_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_57_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38661&sectionno=57&orderno=58&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_57_content:
  string
  line `Where persons`
  line `reciprocally promise, firstly, to do certain things which are legal, and, secondly, under specified`
  line `circumstances, to do certain other things which are illegal, the first set of promises is a contract, but the`
  line `second is a void agreement.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A and B agree that A shall sell B a house for 10,000 rupees, but that, if B uses it as a gambling house, he shall pay A 50,000`
  line `rupees for it.`
  line
  line `The first set of reciprocal promises, namely, to sell the house and to pay 10,000 rupees for it, is a contract.`
  line
  line `The second set is for an unlawful object, namely, that B may use the house as a gambling house, and is a void agreement.`
obj_root_law_sections_57_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_58:
  sectionId (38662)
  sectionNo (58)
  orderNo 59
  title `Alternative promise, one branch being illegal.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_58_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_58_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38662&sectionno=58&orderno=59&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_58_content:
  string
  line `In the case of an alternative promise, one`
  line `branch of which is legal and the other illegal, the legal branch alone can be enforced.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A and B agree that A shall pay B 1,000 rupees, for which B shall afterwards deliver to A either rice or smuggled opium.`
  line
  line `This is a valid contract to deliver rice, and a void agreement as to the opium.`
obj_root_law_sections_58_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_59:
  sectionId (38663)
  sectionNo (59)
  orderNo 60
  title `Application of payment where debt to be discharged is indicated.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_59_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_59_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38663&sectionno=59&orderno=60&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_59_content:
  string
  line `Where a debtor, owing`
  line `several distinct debts to one person, makes a payment to him, either with express intimation, or under`
  line `circumstances implying, that the payment is to be applied to the discharge of some particular debt, the`
  line `payment, if accepted, must be applied accordingly.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A owes B, among other debts, 1,000 rupees upon a promissory note which falls due on the first June. He owes B no other`
  line `debt of that amount. On the first June, A pays to B 1,000 rupees. The payment is to be applied to the discharge of the promissory`
  line note.
  line
  line `(b) A owes to B, among other debts, the sum of 567 rupees. B writes to A and demands payment of this sum. A sends to B`
  line `567 rupees. This payment is to be applied to the discharge of the debt of which B had demanded payment.`
obj_root_law_sections_59_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_60:
  sectionId (38664)
  sectionNo (60)
  orderNo 61
  title `Application of payment where debt to be discharged is not indicated.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_60_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_60_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38664&sectionno=60&orderno=61&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_60_content:
  string
  line `Where the debtor has`
  line `omitted to intimate and there are no other circumstances indicating to which debt the payment is to be`
  line `applied, the creditor may apply it at his discretion to any lawful debt actually due and payable to him from`
  line `the debtor, whether its recovery is or is not barred by the law in force for the time being as to the`
  line `limitation of suits.`
obj_root_law_sections_60_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_61:
  sectionId (38665)
  sectionNo (61)
  orderNo 62
  title `Application of payment where neither party appropriates.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_61_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_61_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38665&sectionno=61&orderno=62&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_61_content:
  string
  line `Where neither party makes any`
  line `appropriation, the payment shall be applied in discharge of the debts in order of time, whether they are or`
  line `are not barred by the law in force for the time being as to the limitation of suits. If the debts are of equal`
  line `standing, the payment shall be applied in discharge of each proportionally.`
obj_root_law_sections_61_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_62:
  sectionId (38666)
  sectionNo (62)
  orderNo 63
  title `Effect of novation, rescission, and alteration of contract.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_62_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_62_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38666&sectionno=62&orderno=63&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_62_content:
  string
  line `If the parties to a contract agree to`
  line `substitute a new contract for it, or to rescind or alter it, the original contract, need not be performed.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A owes money to B under a contract. It is agreed between A, B and C, that B shall thenceforth accept C as his debtor,`
  line `instead of A. The old debt of A to B is at an end, and a new debt from C to B has been contracted.`
  line
  line `(b) A owes B 10,000 rupees. A enters into an arrangement with B, and gives B a mortgage of his (A's) estate for 5,000`
  line `rupees in place of the debt of 10,000 rupees. This is a new contract and extinguishes the old.`
  line
  line `(c) A owes B 1,000 rupees under a contract. B owes C 1,000 rupees, B orders A to credit C with 1,000 rupees in his books,`
  line `but C does not assent to the arrangement. B still owes C 1,000 rupees, and no new contract has been entered into.`
obj_root_law_sections_62_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_63:
  sectionId (38667)
  sectionNo (63)
  orderNo 64
  title `Promise may dispense with or remit performance of promise.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_63_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_63_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38667&sectionno=63&orderno=64&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_63_content:
  string
  line `Every promisee may`
  line `dispense with or remit, wholly or in part, the performance of the promisee made to him, or may extend the`
  line `time for such performance^1`
  line `, or may accept instead of it any satisfaction which he thinks fit.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A promises to paint a picture for B. B afterwards forbids him to do so. A is no longer bound to perform the promise.`
  line
  line `(b) A owes B 5,000 rupees. A pays to B, and B accepts, in satisfaction of the whole debt, 2,000 rupees paid at the time and`
  line `place at which the 5,000 rupees were payable. The whole debt is discharged.`
  line
  line `(c) A owes B 5,000 rupees. C pays to B 1,000 rupees, and B accepts them, in satisfaction of his claim on A. This payment is`
  line `a discharge of the whole claim^2`
  line .
  line
  line `(d) A owes B, under. a contract, a sum of money, the amount of which has not been ascertained. A, without ascertaining the`
  line `amount, gives to B, and B, in satisfaction thereof, accepts, the sum of 2,000 rupees. This is a discharge of the whole debt,`
  line `whatever may be its amount.`
  line
  line `(e) A owes B 2,000 rupees, and is also indebted to other creditors. A makes an arrangement with his creditors, including B,`
  line `to pay them a ^3`
  line `[composition] of eight annas in the rupee upon their respective demands. Payment to B of 1,000 rupees is a`
  line `discharge of B's demand.`
obj_root_law_sections_63_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. But see s. 135, infra.`
  line
  line `2. See s. 41, supra.`
  line
  line `3. Subs. by Act 12 of 1891, s. 2 and the Second Schedule, Pt. I, for "compensation".`
obj_root_law_sections_64:
  sectionId (38668)
  sectionNo (64)
  orderNo 65
  title `Consequences of rescission of voidable contract.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_64_content
  footnotes `1. See s. 75, infra.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38668&sectionno=64&orderno=65&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_64_content:
  string
  line `When a person at whose option a contract is`
  line `voidable rescinds it, the other party thereto need not perform any promise therein contained in which he is`
  line `promisor. The party rescinding avoidable contract shall, if he have received any benefit thereunder from`
  line `another party to such contract, restore such benefit, so far as may be, to the person from whom it was`
  line received.^1
obj_root_law_sections_65:
  sectionId (42836)
  sectionNo (65)
  orderNo 66
  title `Obligation of person who has received advantage under void agreement, or contract that becomes void.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_65_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_65_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=42836&sectionno=65&orderno=66&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_65_content:
  string
  line `When an agreement is discovered to be void, or when a contract becomes void, any person who has received any advantage under such agreement or contract is bound to restore it, or to`
  line `make compensation for it to the person from whom he received it.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A pays B 1,000 rupees, in consideration of B's promising to marry C, A's daughter. C is dead at the time of the promise.`
  line `The agreement is void, but B must repay A the 1,000 rupees.`
  line
  line `(b) A contracts with B to deliver to him 250 maunds of rice before the first of May. A delivers 130 maunds only before that`
  line `day, and none after. B retains the 130 maunds after the first of May. He is bound to pay A for them.`
  line
  line `(c) A, a singer, contracts with B, the manager of a theatre, to sing at his theatre for two nights in every week during the next`
  line `two months, and B engages to pay her a hundred rupees for each nights performance. On the sixth night, A wilfully absents`
  line `herself from the theatre, and B, in consequence, rescinds the contract. B must pay A for the five nights on which she had sung.`
  line
  line `(d) A contracts to sing for B at a concert for 1,000 rupees, which are paid in advance. A is too ill to sing. A is not bound to`
  line `make compensation to B for the loss of the profits which B would have made if A had been able to sing, but must refund to B the`
  line `1,000 rupees paid in advance.`
obj_root_law_sections_65_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_66:
  sectionId (38670)
  sectionNo (66)
  orderNo 67
  title `Mode of communicating or revoking rescission of voidable contract.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_66_content
  footnotes `1. See ss. 3 and 5, supra.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38670&sectionno=66&orderno=67&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_66_content:
  string
  line `The rescission of a`
  line `voidable contract may be communicated or revoked in the same manner, and subject to the same rules, as`
  line `apply to the communication or revocation of a proposal^1`
  line .
obj_root_law_sections_67:
  sectionId (38671)
  sectionNo (67)
  orderNo 68
  title `Effect of neglect of promisee to afford promisor reasonable facilities for performance.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_67_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_67_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38671&sectionno=67&orderno=68&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_67_content:
  string
  line If
  line `any promisee neglects or refuses to afford the promisor reasonable facilities for the performance of his`
  line `promise, the promisor is excused by such neglect or refusal as to any non-performance caused thereby.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A contracts with B to repair B's house.`
  line
  line `B neglects or refuses to point out to A the places in which his house requires repair.`
  line
  line `A is excused for the non-performance of the contract if it is caused by such neglect or refusal.`
obj_root_law_sections_67_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_68:
  sectionId (38672)
  sectionNo (68)
  orderNo 69
  title `Claim for necessaries supplied to person incapable of contracting, or on his account.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_68_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_68_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38672&sectionno=68&orderno=69&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_68_content:
  string
  line `If a`
  line `person, incapable of entering into a contract, or any one whom he is legally bound to support, is supplied`
  line `by another person with necessaries suited to his condition in life, the person who has furnished such`
  line `supplies is entitled to be reimbursed from the property of such incapable person.^1`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A supplies B, a lunatic, with necessaries suitable to his condition in life. A is entitled to be reimbursed from B's`
  line property.
  line
  line `(b) A supplies the wife and children of B, a lunatic, with necessaries suitable to their condition in life. A is entitled to be`
  line `reimbursed from B's property`
obj_root_law_sections_68_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. The property of a Government ward in Madhya Pradeshis not liable under this section, see the C.P. Court of Wards Act, 1899 (24 of`
  line `1899), s. 31(1).`
obj_root_law_sections_69:
  sectionId (38673)
  sectionNo (69)
  orderNo 70
  title `Reimbursement of person paying money due by another, in payment of which he is interested.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_69_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_69_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38673&sectionno=69&orderno=70&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_69_content:
  string
  line `A person who is interested in the payment of money which another is bound by law to pay,`
  line `and who therefore pays it, is entitled to be reimbursed by the other.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `B holds land in Bengal, on a lease granted by A, the zamindar. The revenue payable by A to the Government being in arrear,`
  line `his land is advertised for sale by the Government. Under the revenue law, the consequence of such sale will be the annulment of B's lease. B, to prevent the sale and the consequent annulment of his own lease, pays to the Government the sum due from A. A`
  line `is bound to make good to B the amount so paid.`
obj_root_law_sections_69_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_70:
  sectionId (38674)
  sectionNo (70)
  orderNo 71
  title `Obligation of person enjoying benefit of non-gratuitous act.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_70_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_70_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38674&sectionno=70&orderno=71&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_70_content:
  string
  line `Where a person lawfully does`
  line `anything for another person, or delivers anything to him, not intending to do so gratuitously, and such`
  line `other person enjoys the benefit thereof, the latter is bound to make compensation to the former in respect`
  line `of, or to restore, the thing so done or delivered^1`
  line .
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A, a tradesman, leaves goods at Bs house by mistake. B treats the goods as his own. He is bound to pay A for them.`
  line
  line `(b) A saves Bs property from fire. A is not entitled to compensation from B, if the circumstances show that he intended to`
  line `act gratuitously.`
obj_root_law_sections_70_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. As to suits by minors under s. 70 in Presidency Small Cause Courts, see the Presidency Small Cause Courts Act, 1882`
  line `(15 of 1882), s. 32.`
obj_root_law_sections_71:
  sectionId (38675)
  sectionNo (71)
  orderNo 72
  title `Responsibility of finder of goods.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_71_content
  footnotes `1. See ss. 151 and 152, infra.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38675&sectionno=71&orderno=72&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_71_content:
  string
  line `A person who finds goods belonging to another, and takes`
  line `them into his custody, is subject to the same responsibility as a bailee^1`
  line .
obj_root_law_sections_72:
  sectionId (38676)
  sectionNo (72)
  orderNo 73
  title `Liability of person to whom money is paid, or thing delivered, by mistake or under coercion.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_72_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_72_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38676&sectionno=72&orderno=73&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_72_content:
  string
  line `A person to whom money has been paid, or anything delivered, by mistake or under coercion,`
  line `must repay or return it.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A and B jointly owe 100 rupees to C, A alone pays the amount to C, and B, not knowing this fact, pays 100 rupees over`
  line `again to C. C is bound to repay the amount to B.`
  line
  line `(b) A railway company refuses to deliver up certain goods to the consignee, except upon the payment of an illegal charge for`
  line `carriage. The consignee pays the sum charged in order to obtain the goods. He is entitled to recover so much of the charge as was`
  line `illegally excessive.`
obj_root_law_sections_72_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_73:
  sectionId (38677)
  sectionNo (73)
  orderNo 74
  title `Compensation for loss or damage caused by breach of contract.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_73_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_73_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38677&sectionno=73&orderno=74&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_73_content:
  string
  line `When a contract has been`
  line `broken, the party who suffers by such breach is entitled to receive, from the party who has broken the`
  line `contract, compensation for any loss or damage caused to him thereby, which naturally arose in the usual`
  line `course of things from such breach, or which the parties knew, when they made the contract, to be likely to`
  line `result from the breach of it.`
  line
  line `Such compensation is not to be given for any remote and indirect loss or damage sustained by reason`
  line `of the breach.`
  line
  line `Compensation for failure to discharge obligation resembling those created by contract.When`
  line `an obligation resembling those created by contract has been incurred and has not been discharged, any`
  line `person injured by the failure to discharge it is entitled to receive the same compensation from the party in`
  line `default, as if such person had contracted to discharge it and had broken his contract.`
  line
  line `Explanation.In estimating the loss or damage arising from a breach of contract, the means which`
  line `existed of remedying the inconvenience caused by the non-performance of the contract must be taken into`
  line account.
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A contracts to sell and deliver 50 maunds of saltpetre to B, at a certain price to be paid on delivery. A breaks his promise.`
  line `B is entitled to receive from A, by way of compensation, the sum, if any, by which the contract price falls short of the price for`
  line `which B might have obtained 50 maunds of saltpetre of like quality at the time when the saltpetre ought to have been delivered.`
  line
  line `(b) A hires Bs ship to go to Bombay, and there take on board, on the first of January, a cargo, which A is to provide, and to`
  line `bring it to Calcutta, the freight to be paid when earned. Bs ship does not go to Bombay, but A has opportunities of procuring`
  line `suitable conveyance for the cargo upon terms as advantageous as those on which he had chartered the ship. A avails himself of`
  line `those opportunities, but is put to trouble and expense in doing so. A is entitled to receive compensation from B in respect of such`
  line `trouble and expense.`
  line
  line `(c) A contracts to buy of B, at a stated price, 50 maunds of rice, no time being fixed for delivery. A afterwards informs B`
  line `that he will not accept the rice if tendered to him. B is entitled to receive from A, by way of compensation, the amount, if any, by`
  line `which the contract price exceeds that which B can obtain for the rice at the time when A informs B that he will not accept it.`
  line
  line `(d) A contracts to buy B's ship for 60,000 rupees, but breaks his promise. A must pay to B, by way of compensation, the`
  line `excess, if any, of the contract price over the price which B can obtain for the ship at the time of the breach of promise.`
  line
  line `(e) A, the owner of a boat, contracts with B to take a cargo of jute to Mirzapur, for sale at that place, starting on a specified`
  line `day. The boat, owing to some avoidable cause, does not start at the time appointed, whereby the arrival of the cargo at Mirzapur`
  line `is delayed beyond the time when it would have arrived if the boat had sailed according to the contract. After that date, and before`
  line `the arrival of the cargo, the price of jute falls. The measure of the compensation payable to B by A is the difference between the`
  line `price which B could have obtained for the cargo at Mirzapur at the time when it would have arrived if forwarded in due course,`
  line `and its market price at the time when it actually arrived.`
  line
  line `(f) A contracts to repair B's house in a certain manner, and receives payment in advance. A repairs the house, but not`
  line `according to contract. B is entitled to recover from A the cost of making the repairs conform to the contract.`
  line
  line `(g) A contracts to let his ship to B for a year, from the first of January, for a certain price. Freights rise, and, on the first of`
  line `January, the hire obtainable for the ship is higher than the contract price. A breaks his promise. He must pay to B, by way of`
  line `compensation, a sum equal to the difference between the contract price and the price for which B could hire a similar ship for a`
  line `year on and from the first of January.`
  line
  line `(h) A contracts to supply B with a certain quantity of iron at a fixed price, being a higher price than that for which A could`
  line `procure and deliver the iron. B wrongfully refuses to receive the iron. B must pay to A, by way of compensation, the difference`
  line `between the contract price of the iron and the sum for which A could have obtained and delivered it.`
  line
  line `(i) A delivers to B, a common carrier, a machine, to be conveyed, without delay, to A's mill, informing B that his mill is`
  line `stopped for want of the machine. B unreasonably delays the delivery of the machine, and A, in consequence, loses a profitable`
  line `contract with the Government. A is entitled to receive from B, by way of compensation, the average amount of profit which`
  line `would have been made by the working of the mill during the time that delivery of it was delayed, but not the loss sustained`
  line `through the loss of the Government contract.`
  line
  line `(j) A, having contracted with B to supply B with 1,000 tons of iron at 100 rupees a ton, to be delivered at a stated time,`
  line `contracts with C for the purchase of 1,000 tons of iron at 80 rupees a ton, telling C that he does so for the purpose of performing`
  line `his contract with B. C fails to perform his contract with A, who cannot procure other iron, and B, in consequence, rescinds the`
  line `contract. C must pay to A 20,000 rupees, being the profit which A would have made by the performance of his contract with B.`
  line
  line `(k) A contracts with B to make and deliver to B, by a fixed day, for a specified price, a certain piece of machinery. A does`
  line `not deliver the piece of machinery at the time specified, and in consequence of this, B is obliged to procure another at a higher`
  line `piece than that which he was to have paid to A, and is prevented from performing a contract which B had made with a third`
  line `person at the time of his contract with A (but which had not been then communicated to A), and is compelled to make`
  line `compensation for breach of that contract. A must pay to B, by way of compensation, the difference between the contract price of`
  line `the price of machinery and the sum paid by B for another, but not the sum paid by B to the third person by way of compensation.`
  line
  line `(l) A, a builder, contracts to erect and finish a house by the first of January, in order that B may give possession of it at that`
  line `time to C, to whom B has contracted to let it. A is informed of the contract between B and C. A builds the house so badly that,`
  line `before the first of January, it falls down and has to be re-built by B, who, in consequence, loses the rent which he was to have`
  line `received from C, and is obliged to make compensation to C for the breach of his contract. A must make compensation to B for`
  line `the cost of rebuilding the house, for the rent lost, and for the compensation made to C.`
  line
  line `(m) A sells certain merchandise to B, warranting it to be of a particular quality, and B, in reliance upon this warranty, sells it`
  line `to C with a similar warranty. The goods prove to be not according to the warranty, and B becomes liable to pay C a sum of`
  line `money by way of compensation. B is entitled to be reimbursed this sum by A.`
  line
  line `(n) A contracts to pay a sum of money to B on a day specified. A does not pay the money on that day, B, in consequence of`
  line `not receiving the money on that day, is unable to pay his debts, and is totally ruined. A is not liable to make good to B anything`
  line `except the principal sum he contracted to pay, together with interest up to the day of payment.`
  line
  line `(o) A contracts to deliver 50 maunds of saltpetre to B on the first of January, at a certain price. B afterwards, before the first`
  line `of January, contracts to sell the saltpetre to C at a price higher than the market price of the first of January. A breaks his promise.`
  line
  line `In estimating the compensation payable by A to B, the market price of the first of January, and not the profit which would`
  line `have arisen to B from the sale to C, is to be taken into account.`
  line
  line `(p) A contracts to sell and deliver 500 bales of cotton to B on a fixed day. A knows nothing of Bs mode of conducting his`
  line `business. A breaks his promise, and B, having no cotton, is obliged to close his mill. A is not responsible to B for the loss caused`
  line `to B by the closing of the mill.`
  line
  line `(q) A contracts to sell and deliver to B, on the first of January, certain cloth which B intends to manufacture into caps of a`
  line `particular kind, for which there is no demand, except at that season. The cloth is not delivered till after the appointed time, and`
  line `too late to be used that year in making caps. B is entitled to receive from A, by way of compensation, the difference between the`
  line `contract price of the cloth and its market price at the time of delivery, but not the profits which he expected to obtain by making`
  line `caps, nor the expenses which he has been put to in making preparation for the manufacture.`
  line
  line `(r) A, a ship-owner, contracts with B to convey him from Calcutta to Sydney in A's ship, sailing on the first of January, and`
  line `B pays to A, by way of deposit, one-half of his passage-money. The ship does not sail on the first of January, and B, after being`
  line `in consequence detained in Calcutta for some time and thereby put to some expense, proceeds to Sydney in another vessel, and,`
  line `in consequence, arriving too late in Sydney, loses a sum of money. A is liable to repay to B his deposit, with interest, and the`
  line `expense to which he is put by his detention in Calcutta, and the excess, if any, of the passage-money paid for the second ship over`
  line `that agreed upon for the first, but not the sum of money which B lost by arriving in Sydney too late.`
obj_root_law_sections_73_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_74:
  sectionId (38678)
  sectionNo (74)
  orderNo 75
  title `Compensation for breach of contract where penalty stipulated for.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_74_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_74_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38678&sectionno=74&orderno=75&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_74_content:
  string
  line `^1[When a contract has`
  line `been broken, if a sum is named in the contract as the amount to be paid in case of such breach, or if the`
  line `contract contains any other stipulation by way of penalty, the party complaining of the breach is entitled,`
  line `whether or not actual damage or loss is proved to have been caused thereby, to receive from the party who`
  line `has broken the contract reasonable compensation not exceeding the amount so named or, as the case may`
  line `be, the penalty stipulated for.`
  line
  line `Explanation.-- A stipulation for increased interest from the date of default may be a stipulation by`
  line `way of penalty.]`
  line
  line `Exception.-- When any person enters into any bail-bond, recognizance or other instrument of the`
  line `same nature, or, under the provisions of any law, or under the orders of the ^2`
  line `[Central Government] or of`
  line `any ^3[State Government], gives any bond for the performance of any public duty or act in which the`
  line `public are interested, he shall be liable, upon breach of the condition of any such instrument, to pay the`
  line `whole sum mentioned therein.`
  line
  line `Explanation.-- A person who enters into a contract with Government does not necessarily thereby`
  line `undertake any public duty, or promise to do an act in which the public are interested.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A contracts with B to pay B Rs. 1,000, if he fails to pay B Rs. 500 on a given day. A fails to pay B Rs. 500 on that day. B`
  line `is entitled to recover from A such compensation, not exceeding Rs. 1,000, as the Court considers reasonable.`
  line
  line `(b) A contracts with B that, if A practises as a surgeon within Calcutta, he will pay B Rs. 5,000. A practises as a surgeon in`
  line `Calcutta. B is entitled to such compensation; not exceeding Rs. 5,000, as the Court considers reasonable.`
  line
  line `(c) A gives a recognizance binding him in a penalty of Rs. 500 to appear in Court on a certain day. He forfeits his`
  line `recognizance. He is liable to pay the whole penalty.`
  line
  line ^4
  line `[(d) A gives B a bond for the repayment of Rs. 1,000 with interest at 12 per cent. at the end of six months, with a stipulation`
  line `that, in case of default, interest shall be payable at the rate of 75 per cent. from the date of default. This is a stipulation by way of`
  line `penalty, and B is only entitled to recover from A such compensation as the Court considers reasonable.`
  line
  line `(e) A, who owes money to B a money-lender, undertakes to repay him by delivering to him 10 maunds of grain on a certain`
  line `date, and stipulates that, in the event of his not delivering the stipulated amount by the stipulated date, he shall be liable to deliver`
  line `20 maunds. This is a stipulation by way of penalty, and B is only entitled to reasonable compensation in case of breach.`
  line
  line `(f) A undertakes to repay B a loan of Rs. 1,000 by five equal monthly instalments, with a stipulation that in default of`
  line `payment of any instalment, the whole shall become due. This stipulation is not by way of penalty, and the contract may be`
  line `enforced according to its terms.`
  line
  line `(g) A borrows Rs. 100 from B and gives him a bond for Rs. 200 payable by five yearly instalments of Rs. 40, with a`
  line `stipulation that, in default of payment of any instalment, the whole shall become due. This is a stipulation by way of penalty.]`
obj_root_law_sections_74_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. Subs. by Act 6 of 1899, s. 4, for the first paragraph of s. 74.`
  line
  line `2. Subs. by the A.O. 1937, for "Government of India".`
  line
  line `3. Subs. by the A.O. 1950, for "Provincial Government".`
  line
  line `4. Added by Act 6 of 1899, s. 4.`
obj_root_law_sections_75:
  sectionId (38679)
  sectionNo (75)
  orderNo 76
  title `Party rightfully rescinding contract, entitled to compensation.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_75_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_75_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428&sectionId=38679&sectionno=75&orderno=76&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00035_187209_1523268996428
obj_root_law_sections_75_content:
  string
  line `A person who rightfully`
  line `rescinds a contract is entitled to compensation for any damage which he has sustained through the`
  line `non-fulfilment of the contract.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A, a singer, contracts with B, the manager of a theatre, to sing at his theatre for two nights in every week during the next two`
  line `months, and B engages to pay her 100 rupees for each night's performance. On the sixth night, A wilfully absents herself from`
  line `the theatre, and B, in consequence, rescinds the contract. B is entitled to claim compensation for the damage which he has`
  line `sustained through the non-fulfilment of the contract`
obj_root_law_sections_75_footnotes:
  string
  line
